acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: The collection has been donated to the Rockefeller Archive Center by RBF.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Rockefeller Brothers Fund (RBF) was established in 1940 by the five sons of John D. Rockefeller Jr. and Abby Aldrich Rockefeller: John D. 3rd, Nelson A., Laurance S., Winthrop, and David Rockefeller, as a vehicle for the members of the Brothers generation to systematically coordinate their philanthropic giving as well as share consultants, advice, and resources. Its endowment was created through a gift from JDR Jr. in 1951, and a subsequent bequest from his estate in 1960. Abby Rockefeller Mauz√©, the eldest sibling and the only daughter of John D. Jr. and Abby Aldrich Rockefeller, joined the RBF Board in 1954.

John D. Rockefeller 3rd served as president of the Fund from its inception until 1956. Other past presidents have included: Nelson A. Rockefeller, 1956-1958; Laurance S. Rockefeller, 1958-1968; Dana S. Creel, 1968-1975; William M. Dietel, 1975-1987; and Colin G. Campbell, 1998-2000.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The project files include grant administration records, correspondence, reports, grant actions, grant products, and other associated material that document the philanthropic work of the Rockefeller Brothers Fund.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. Researchers interested in accessing digital media (floppy disks, CDs, DVDs, etc.) or audiovisual material (audio cassettes, VHS, etc.) in this collection must use an access surrogate. The original items may not be accessed because of preservation concerns. To request an access surrogate be made, or if you are unsure if there is an access surrogate, please contact an archivist.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: Grant-making is the core of Rockefeller Brothers Fund operations. The RBF makes grants to local, national, and international philanthropic organizations that depend on the general public for funding. Principally, contributions are made to organizations whose activities reach a large number of people. The RBF's program has also included support for, and in some instances direct operation of, experimental or new undertakings.
RG 3 Project/Grant Files includes correspondence, memoranda, reports, financial records, and background material relating to grant applications and grant administration.

Each file contains records documenting the grant-giving history of the RBF with that given institution. They are not arranged by grant number. The files are presented alphabetically by the institutional name of the grant recipient, and further arranged by date. A specific institution may have received more than one grant for any given time period represented in the folder. Dates are inclusive, and reflect the dates of material within the folders; they can not be taken to represent continuous support, although in some cases continuous support may indeed have been given.
The distinction between Subgroup 1 and Subgroup 2 is artificial, primarily dependent on the date that the material was shipped to RAC.
Record Group 3.1, Box 1-1123 (561.5 cu. ft.), consists of material dated 1941-1989 and received by RAC through 1990.
Record Group 3.2, Box 1124-1492 (184.5 cu. ft.), consists of material dated 1967-2003 (bulk: 1980-1995) and received by RAC after 1990.
Documentation of the grant activity of a given institution may appear in both Subgroups.

Subjects include civic improvement, cultural advancement, education, health, religion, welfare, international relations and understanding, conservation, population, and racial equality in the United States and abroad.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The Project/Grant files are arranged into two subgroups. Each subgroup is arranged alphabetically by institutional name of the grant recipient.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Material ten years old or older is open for research

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Materials
separatedmaterial.p: Books and publications which were originally contained in the grant files have been systematically separated to the RAC Library. Photographs and special format materials have been separated from their original location within specific grant files to best meet their preservation and conservation needs. Please refer to the inventory, and to the individual separation notes found in the files themselves, for applicable details.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: RBF retains legal title, copyright and literary property rights in the records, in so far as they hold them.

The Rockefeller Archive Center has authority to grant permission to cite and publish material from the RBF records. Requests to publish works in their entirety will be referred to the officers of the Rockefeller Brothers Fund.
